   <text>
      <body>
         <div type="letter">
            <pb n="1" facs="Edgeworth_Beinecke_330_1816_08_23_page01.jpg"/>
            <!--filenames for photos associated with this letter. Example: <pb n="1" facs="image1.jpg image2.jpg image3.jpg"/> -->
            <opener>
               <dateline><!--If there's no date line, omit this element. Record in the order in which it is written on the letter.-->
                  <name type="place" ref="Id_where"/>Stoke Newington
                  <date when="1816-08-23"/>August 23<hi rend = "superscript">d</hi>. 1816</dateline>
               <salute>
                  <persName>
                     <!-- Use if letter has a saluation ("Dear Sir," for example). If not, delete this line.-->
                     Dear madam,
                  </persName>
               </salute>
            </opener>
            <p>
               Will you permit me to address you, conscious as<lb/>
               I am that I have neglected the advantage &amp; the honour of that<lb/>
               intercourse by letter which my heart all the while acknowledged in<lb/>
               its fullest extent. What an excellent &amp; what a cruel piece is your<lb/>
               <title><hi rend ="underline">To Morrow</hi></title>! How you could enter so well into feelings which your<lb/>
               activity &amp; strength of mind must have hindered you from partaking<lb/>
               I cannot imagine, but to me it has given many a twinge of<lb/>
               conscience, &amp; most particularly in the affair of letter writing which, if<lb/>
               I have happenned to delay a little too long, always becomes difficult to me<lb/>
               beyond imagination. Days pass, &amp; the more honour &amp; esteem I have for my<lb/>
               correspondent, the more I feel that I have nothing worth communicating<lb/>
               &amp; my brain feels dry, - "<hi rend = "underline">as the remaining biscuit</hi> -<lb/>
               <hi rend = "underline">after a voyage</hi>". With regard to yourself, tho longing to write, I<lb/>
               doubt if I should have had the courage, but for a hint communi-<lb/>
               cated by <persName>M[superscript]rs[/superscript] Baillie</persName> intimating that I might have taken amiss not<lb/>
               seeing more of you <add>when you were in <placeName>London</placeName></add>. Oh my dear <persName>Miss Edgeworth</persName>, I cannot<lb/>
               bear you should think so for a moment. Much as I value<lb/>
               your<lb/>
               <pb n="2" facs="Edgeworth_Beinecke_330_1816_08_23_page02.jpg"/>
               your society, I well know the demands on your time, I know the<lb/>
               homage paid you &amp; I exulted in it for your sake &amp; for my sex's<lb/>
               sake - And now will you forgive me? Will you now receive all the<lb/>
               acknowledgements I owe you, both in common with all those who have<lb/>
               been delighted &amp; instructed by your charming works, &amp; more particularly<lb/>
               as having received them from your hands. Long may you continue<lb/>
               to delight the world with livelier wit &amp; humour than those who write<lb/>
               merely for amusement, &amp; with juster &amp; more impressive sentiments of<lb/>
               morality than most of those who write merely for instruction -<lb/></p>
               <p>
               I should ask you if could resist the general spirit of migration &amp; stay<lb/>
                  at home when <placeName>England</placeName> is pouring itself over the continent, if I did<lb/>
                  not hear, &amp; very sorry I am to hear it, that <persName>M<hi rend = "superscript">r</hi>Edgeworth's</persName> state of health<lb/>
                  is such as must prevent your leaving him. I tremble to think what <unclear>tours</unclear><lb/>
               must be preparing for the press, what sweeping characters of nations will be<lb/>
               given by the traveller who has dined two or three times at a table d'hôte,<lb/>
                  &amp; how after we shall be sick between <placeName>Dover</placeName> &amp; <placeName>Calais</placeName> - I am wishing to<lb/>
               lay a tax on English Absentees, not the tourist of a few months, but the<lb/>
               Nobleman who dismisses his servants, shuts up his mansion, &amp; spends his vast<lb/>
                  rents abroad - Pray have you had any Summer in <placeName>Ireland</placeName>? We have<lb/>
               not. A weeping, chilling, hope disappointing summer, if we must call<lb/>
               it such, but that it might not entirely want energy, we have<lb/>
               had<lb/>
               <pb n="3" facs="Edgeworth_Beinecke_330_1816_08_23_page03.jpg"/>
                  had, it seems, an earthquake in <placeName>Scotland</placeName> - A Summer without heat<lb/>
                  is like a youth without affections, there is nothing to cheer the damp<lb/>
                  &amp; dreary season which succeeds it. I have myself felt much want of<lb/>
                  some enlivening influence to counteract the languor of age &amp; the<lb/>
                  dreainess of a solitary house. Writing <del>any</del> any thing I have not<lb/>
                  felt equal to, &amp; reading has at times been a task to me, but at present<lb/>
                  I feel better. Everyone here has not been so idle, Perhaps you have<lb/>
                  seen my <persName>Brother's</persName> <title><hi rend = "underline">Annals</hi></title> &amp; tho necessarily somewhat dry from the<lb/>
                  necessary compression of such an eventful period, I think you will have<lb/>
                  been pleased with the fairness &amp; impartiality with which they are<lb/>
                  written.<unclear></unclear> My neice, <persName>Miss Aikin</persName>, has made some progress in <unclear></unclear><lb/>
                  <hi rend = "underline">Memoirs of the reign of Elizabeth</hi>. She is taking great <unclear>pains with</unclear><lb/>
                  it &amp; I hope it will answer her expectation &amp; her friends' - We are<lb/>
                  expecting every day another Canto of <hi rend = "underline"><title>Child Harold</title></hi>, but I apprehend the<lb/>
                  <persName>Author</persName> has lost too much of the public favour by his late cruel behaviour to<lb/>
                  <persName>his wife</persName> to be as popular as he has been. I have now upon my table the<lb/>
                  strangest Poem - <persName>Wilson's</persName> <hi rend = "underline"><title>City of the Plague</title></hi>, a heap of horrors natural &amp;<lb/>
                  moral - and <hi rend = "underline"><persName>Lee Hunt's</persName> <title>Rimini</title></hi>, the most fantastic. Thus it is when<lb/>
                  the natural &amp; easy has become a beaten path &amp; the intellectual taste<lb/>
                  wants excitement, as the sensitive by more pungent relishes the originally<lb/>
                  disagreeable - My dear Madam have I not tired you? Will<lb/>
                  you forgive me? Will you love me, little as I may deserve it<lb/>
                  will<lb/> 
                  <pb n="4" facs="Edgeworth_Beinecke_330_1816_08_23_page04.jpg"/>
                  Will you convey my respectful Compliments to <persName>M<hi rend = "superscript">r</hi></persName> &amp; <persName>M<hi rend = "superscript">rs</hi> Edgeworth</persName><lb/>
                  &amp; best wishes for all your family, &amp; will you believe me with<lb/>
                  the highest esteem &amp; most affectionate good wishes,<lb/>
                  I beg you to believe that I have written this<lb/>
                  upon the <hi rend = "underline">knees</hi> of my <hi rend = "underline">heart</hi><lb/>
            </p>
            <closer>
               <!--include linebreaks, if used. example: <closer> Yours<lb/> Very sincerely<lb/> -->
               Your ever obliged<lb/>
               <persName>A L Barbauld</persName>
            </closer>
